	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Liberalisation of the EU tuna market is described as ‘economic suicide’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 September 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> At the conference on tuna held at the headquarters of the Spanish National Association of Producers and Manufactures of Seafood Products (ANFACO) in Vigo (Spain) on September 11th 2006, it was announced that Spain has quadrupled its canned-tuna production during the last 20 years, from 60,000 tons in 1986 to 240,512 tons in 2004. This makes Spain the second largest producer in the world after Thailand. The conference was attended by representatives of 90% of the world producing countries, including official delegations from ACP countries such as Côte d’Ivoire and Mauritius. </p><p> Participants from the EU tuna sector said that full liberalisation of the EU tuna market would open it up to massive imports from Asian countries. They described it as ‘economic suicide’ for the EU, as it will lead to major job losses and closures. The president of the French tuna sector explained that the EU tuna industry was reaching its profitability limits, given the rising costs of raw material, due to decreasing catches, and the high price of fuel for the fishing fleets. Several representatives from the Spanish canned-tuna sector insisted on the fact that new EU member states were their natural markets. The ten new member states that joined the EU in 2004 represent a population of almost 90 millions, most notably Poland, that accounts for 40 millions inhabitants and is an important fish consumer. </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> ATUNA website news, September 11th 2006</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuned.biz/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=3806" target="_self">http://www.atuned.biz/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=3806</a> </p><p><i>Voz de Galicia</i>, news article (in Spanish), September 12th 2006</p><p>
<a href="http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/se_maritima/noticia.jsp?CAT=109&amp;TEXTO=5098301Voz" target="_self">http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/se_maritima/noticia.jsp?CAT=109&amp;TEXTO=5...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/se_maritima/noticia.jsp?CAT=109&amp;TEXTO=5098301Voz" target="_self"> <i>Voz</i> </a> de Galicia, news article (in Spanish), September 13th 2006</p><p>
<i>
<a href="http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/se_maritima/noticia.jsp?CAT=109&amp;TEXTO=5101030" target="_self">http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/se_maritima/noticia.jsp?CAT=109&amp;TEXTO=5...</a> </i> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> While the EU tuna sector keeps warning of the socio-economic consequences of tuna-trade liberalisation, it is also looking at how to adapt to it. This includes expanding their markets in new EU member states, and relocating some of their operations to third, non-ACP countries, that will soon benefit from such liberalisation.</p><p> The EU tuna sector’s agenda may match the ACP’s in defending traditional preference schemes against full liberalisation of the sector. But the ACP should bear in mind that this alliance will only stand so long as tuna production in ACP countries remains attractive for the EU tuna sector. In that light, they need to clarify their priorities for the long-term development of their tuna sectors, as much in terms of resource management, as for the allocation of access rights to various users, and processing and marketing. Where the chosen model of production is based on access by foreign fishing fleets to local tuna resources, it may be worthwhile looking at ways to make such access conditional on local investment, particularly in on-shore handling, processing and infrastructure facilities.</p>
		</div>
		
